{{Merge from|Telial stage|date=August 2018}}
[[File:Gymnosporangium telia macro IMGP0418.jpg|thumb|right|Close-up of ''Gymnosporangium clavariiforme'' telia emerging from ''Juniperus communis'' bark]] [[File:Teliospores 0433.jpg|thumb|right|Micrograph of two teliospores from telia of ''Gymnosporangium clavariiforme]] '''Telium''', plural '''telia''', are structures produced by [[Rust (fungus)|rust fungi]] as part of the [[reproductive cycle]].<ref>Brand g, Brand R & Shattock R,.Sorting out ''Gymnosporangium species - the aecial stage'', October 2006, Field Mycology Volume 7(4)</ref> They are typically yellow or orange drying to brown or black and are exclusively a mechanism for the release of [[teliospore]]s which are released by wind or water to infect the alternate [[Host (biology)|host]] in the rust life-cycle.
